John’s Weight Gain Delimma

Author

Ikenna Atum

Published

February 17, 2026

Problem: An inquiry into a heavy phenomenon

John is one of the best bakers in the San Fernando Valley. People come far and wide to try his out of this world Focaccia bread. His resturant “The D’oo Boys” has gotten amazing reviews in leading publications such as the LA Times and The SF Chronicle. Though he is considered the master of Focaccia lately he has had something else on his mind, weight gain.

John works alot of long hours at the resturant. This along with poor dietary choices has led to him gaining a bit of weight. He was been talking to his friend Nicole, who is a nutritionist, about strategies to lose weight. John is convinced if he sleeps more he can just lose all the weight. However Nicole is advising him that there could be other factors that could lead to more weight gain. She has recommended that he visit his primary care physician to get a check up and create an action plan to lose the weight. To illustrate her point, however, Nicole is going to perform an inferential analysis on a group of individuals to see how different factors influence their weight.

Problem/Stake Holders

Problem: John is gaining weight and he wants to lose it Stake holders: John the Business owner and Nicole the Nutritionist

Data Sources

The data comes from the NHANES Dataset from NHANES

Conclusion: Recomendations for the issue

After running through some analysis of the data, we can see that there were many other factors that influenced the weight of the participants in this study. Things like age, household income, and height all had a hand in determining the weight of the participants in the study. After meeting with his Primary care Doctor, John should consider some lifestyle changes that could help him reduce his weight.

Create the recipe() for applying the preprocessing using prep(). Note the use of step_nzv(), which removes any columns that have very low variability, and the use of the step_impute_median() function, which fills in the cells that are missing with the median of the column.

NHANES_weight_recipe <- training(NHANES_weight_split) |>
  recipe(Weight ~ .) |>
  step_nzv(all_predictors()) |>
  step_impute_knn(all_predictors()) |>
  step_corr(all_numeric()) |>
  prep()
